Cell.Data: Ordering of medication for patient or group

NB Implementation Guide does not have separate Medication Request CeRX Message type, prescription is inferred when available from dispense message: PORX_IN020190CA/PORX_MT020070CA/medicationDispense/component3/supplyEvent/product/COCT_MT220200CA/medication
active | on-hold | cancelled | completed | entered-in-error | stopped | draft | unknown

This element is labeled as a modifier because the status contains codes that mark the resource as not currently valid.
Atlantic Implementors need to be aware that the Act Status Codes recommended by CeRX only partially match the codes to the MedicationRequest status (required) value set
True if request is prohibiting action

If only a code is specified, then it needs to be a code for a specific product. If more information is required, then the use of the Medication resource is recommended. For example, if you require form or lot number or if the medication is compounded or extemporaneously prepared, then you must reference the Medication resource.
Implementors need to be aware that the medication codes utilized by the source DIS will likely come from the Clinical Drug CeRX value set (https://infocentral.infoway-inforoute.ca/extra/ns/cerx43-html/html/vocabulary.html?type=vs&id=ClinicalDrug) which draws in codes from various other code systems (HC-DIN, HC-NPN, HC-AIGC, etc.). There is currently no equivilant FHIR value set that supports this superset to recommend when binding.

Cell.Data: Canadian Clinical Drug Data (CCDD) Medicinal Products

Medicinal products for prescribing. The content of this subset only contains commonly used medicinal products that are available for prescribing and dispensing in Canada. This content will expand to include all human medicinal products over time.
A coded value denoting drug identification at various levels of abstraction. Examples include identification system for manufactured drug product, generic formulation, generic, and therapeutic class.
Contains a set of coordinated information related to a diagnosis or health condition.
Codes used to identify different types of 'duration-based' working lists. Examples include "Continuous/Chronic", "Short-Term" and "As-Needed".
The set of body locations to or through which a drug product may be administered.
This is the means by which a substance is to be admiinistered to the patient.
Identifies the types of substitution that may be permitted when ordering a medication, as well as those which have actually occurred during the act of dispensing.
Indicates the reason for substitution when substitution is not expected, or reason for non-substitution when substitution is expected.
This value set includes all drug or medicament substance codes and all pharmaceutical/biologic products from SNOMED CT - provided as an exemplar value set.
Example value set for Condition/Problem/Diagnosis codes.
v3 Code System ActCode (ActMedicationTherapyDurationWorkingList codes can be found within this value set)
v3 Act Substance Admin Substitution Code
v3 Act Substance Admin Substitution Code Value Set
The set of body locations to or through which a drug product may be administered.

A set of codes specifying the motivation, cause, or rationale of an Act, when such rationale is not reasonably represented as an ActRelationship of type "has reason" linking to another Act. Examples: Example reasons that might qualify for being coded in this field might be: "routine requirement", "infectious disease reporting requirement", "on patient request", "required by law".
